WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:24.680
Cheedub presents American Folk Tales by George Gibson.

00:30.000 --> 00:56.000
The Legend of Johnny Appleseed Part 1 Johnny and his Apple Seeds

00:56.000 --> 01:05.000
Johnny Appleseed was born near Boston in 1775. His real name was John Chapman.

01:05.000 --> 01:13.000
When he was a child, he played in the forest and in the fields. His best friends were animals.

01:13.000 --> 01:22.000
He loved all animals. He played with them and talked to them. His family was very religious.

01:22.000 --> 01:29.000
Johnny's first book was the Bible, but he also liked Asop's Fables.

01:29.000 --> 01:34.000
Johnny loved the tales about animals and their adventures.

01:34.000 --> 01:43.000
When Johnny was a teenager, he worked as a missionary with the Indians. He converted many Indians to Christianity.

01:43.000 --> 01:50.000
He taught them about the Bible. The Indians were his friends.

01:50.000 --> 01:59.000
When he was 26 years old, he had a vision. An angel appeared to him. The angel said,

01:59.000 --> 02:08.000
Go and plant apple seeds across America. The settlers of the new frontier want good apples to eat.

02:08.000 --> 02:16.000
Johnny was surprised, but he was happy. He was a kind person and he wanted to help others.

02:16.000 --> 02:23.000
He took a big sack and filled it with apple seeds. He carried this sack on his back.

02:23.000 --> 02:30.000
In one hand, he carried the Bible, Asop's Fables, and other religious books.

02:30.000 --> 02:37.000
Now he was ready to cross the continent and plant America's favorite fruit, the apple.

02:37.000 --> 02:48.000
Johnny was an unusual man. He was tall and thin. He had long hair and a beard. He never bought new clothes.

02:48.000 --> 02:56.000
He wore an old coffee sack and the old clothes people gave him. He didn't usually wear any shoes.

02:56.000 --> 03:02.000
He wore a saucepan on his head. One of Johnny's friends said,

03:02.000 --> 03:10.000
God bless you, Johnny. We are happy for you. You are similar to St. Francis of Assisi.

03:10.000 --> 03:14.000
He loved animals and lived a simple life.

03:14.000 --> 03:26.000
Johnny said, I want to plant apple seeds across America. Every American family will have apple trees with good apples to eat.

03:27.000 --> 03:36.000
In 1800, Johnny began his long journey across America. At that time, America was a very young country.

03:36.000 --> 03:45.000
The American continent was a wilderness. It was unexplored. There were no roads and few maps.

03:45.000 --> 03:55.000
This immense land was called the American frontier. Many settlers wanted to explore the frontier.

03:55.000 --> 04:02.000
Johnny walked from Massachusetts to New York. From New York, he walked to Pennsylvania.

04:02.000 --> 04:11.000
Then he crossed Ohio, Indiana, and a big part of the Midwest. Every day he moved west.

04:11.000 --> 04:21.000
He traveled across America and planted apple seeds. He built fences around the fields and then continued his journey.

04:21.000 --> 04:32.000
Settlers traveled to the frontier and found the apple orchards. They ate the delicious fruit, green, red, and yellow apples.

04:32.000 --> 04:37.000
When the settlers found an apple orchard, they built a home there.

04:37.000 --> 04:48.000
Other settlers dug up the apple trees and took them to New Lands. Some of Johnny's trees traveled to the West Coast on the Pacific Ocean.

04:49.000 --> 04:58.000
When Johnny found a family of settlers, he visited their log cabin. He helped them with their work.

04:58.000 --> 05:08.000
He told the children's stories and sang songs. One day Johnny visited a family of settlers in the Midwest.

05:08.000 --> 05:15.000
This family loved books. He gave them a few pages from his books.

05:15.000 --> 05:23.000
You can read them and give them to me when I return in a few months. He said, the family was very happy.

05:23.000 --> 05:35.000
In this way, Johnny created the first library on the frontier. Many children learned to read thanks to Johnny and his library.

05:38.000 --> 05:42.000
American food made with apples.

05:42.000 --> 05:50.000
Americans eat a lot of green, yellow, and red apples. There was a lot of food and drink made with apples.

05:50.000 --> 05:57.000
Here is a proverb. An apple a day keeps the doctor away.

05:57.000 --> 06:02.000
Apples are a delicious fruit and are very good for you.

06:02.000 --> 06:10.000
Today, in the United States, there are more than 7,000 different kinds of apples.

06:11.000 --> 06:16.000
At Halloween, children in America bob for apples.

06:20.000 --> 06:24.000
Part 2. Johnny becomes a legend.

06:27.000 --> 06:37.000
For many years, Johnny walked thousands of miles across the frontier. He planted apple seeds, lent books, protected animals,

06:37.000 --> 06:47.000
and made friends with settlers and Indians. The Indians liked Johnny because he had no weapons and respected nature.

06:47.000 --> 06:52.000
Johnny learned to speak the languages of many tribes.

06:52.000 --> 07:02.000
One summer morning, many Indians arrived at a frontier village. The Indians wanted to destroy the village and kill the settlers.

07:02.000 --> 07:13.000
The settlers wanted to send a messenger to a military fort to ask for help. The fort was 30 miles away. It was very dangerous.

07:13.000 --> 07:16.000
There were enemy Indians everywhere.

07:16.000 --> 07:27.000
Johnny wanted to save the lives of the settlers. He knew all the secret paths in the forest and in the mountains. He was not afraid.

07:28.000 --> 07:37.000
He took the message to the fort. The soldiers at the fort got on their horses and went to defend the settlers.

07:37.000 --> 07:45.000
A few years later, Johnny visited an Indian village. He heard the Indian chief say,

07:45.000 --> 07:52.000
Many settlers live near the river. Tonight, we will kill all of them.

07:52.000 --> 07:57.000
That evening, Johnny ran to the home of every settler and said,

07:57.000 --> 08:03.000
The Indians will attack you tonight. Run away. Go and hide in the forest.

08:03.000 --> 08:08.000
The settlers escaped to the forest and no one was killed.

08:08.000 --> 08:19.000
Johnny loved all forms of human and animal life. He didn't eat meat because he didn't want to kill animals. He loved insects too.

08:19.000 --> 08:26.000
He loved and respected every living thing. He was a very special person.

08:26.000 --> 08:37.000
One autumn day, Johnny was near an apple orchard. He heard the cry of an animal. Behind a tree, he found a deer.

08:37.000 --> 08:46.000
My poor friend said Johnny. Don't be afraid. He examined the deer and said,

08:46.000 --> 08:52.000
Your leg is injured. I can help you. The deer wasn't afraid.

08:52.000 --> 08:57.000
Johnny stayed with the deer for many days and helped it.

08:57.000 --> 09:03.000
I'm happy you can walk again. Go and run in the forest, my little friend.

09:03.000 --> 09:13.000
During a snowstorm, Johnny wanted to sleep inside a small cave. He saw a big family of raccoons sleeping inside the cave.

09:13.000 --> 09:20.000
He did not want the raccoons to go outside into the snow, so Johnny slept outside in the cold.

09:20.000 --> 09:27.000
For almost 50 years, Johnny Appleseed helped the American frontier to grow.

09:27.000 --> 09:36.000
His apple trees, his books, his generosity and his kindness made the frontier a happy place.

09:36.000 --> 09:41.000
Johnny became a legend during his life. Everyone loved him.

09:41.000 --> 09:47.000
He was a true friend of the settlers, the Indians and the animals.

09:47.000 --> 09:51.000
In America today, people remember him with admiration.

09:51.000 --> 10:00.000
When Americans eat an apple, they often think of Johnny Appleseed, who made apple trees grow all over America.

10:06.000 --> 10:10.000
Young America and its settlers.

10:10.000 --> 10:20.000
When Johnny Appleseed was born in 1775, America was not a nation. It was an English colony.

10:20.000 --> 10:26.000
America became a nation after the American Revolution.

10:26.000 --> 10:31.000
The enormous American continent was a wilderness.

10:31.000 --> 10:38.000
There were unexplored forests, mountains, rivers, lakes, fields and deserts.

10:38.000 --> 10:44.000
Only the American Indians lived in small parts of this wilderness.

10:44.000 --> 10:50.000
The American army sent its soldiers to build forts in the wilderness.

10:50.000 --> 10:58.000
These forts were similar to small villages. They protected settlers from Indian attacks.

10:58.000 --> 11:07.000
They also sold supplies. Settlers often built their log cabins near military forts.

11:08.000 --> 11:14.000
Thousands of settlers wanted to live in these new lands. It was their dream.

11:14.000 --> 11:20.000
The settlers didn't usually buy the land. It was free from the government.

11:20.000 --> 11:24.000
Families of settlers traveled in covered wagons.

11:24.000 --> 11:30.000
These covered wagon trains traveled long distances to new lands.

11:30.000 --> 11:36.000
Settlers were strong, courageous people. Life on the frontier was not easy.

11:36.000 --> 11:40.000
It was difficult and dangerous.

11:40.000 --> 11:44.000
The men built log cabins and hunted for food.

11:44.000 --> 11:50.000
The women and children worked as farmers. There was little free time.

11:50.000 --> 12:02.000
The settlers were happy. They loved the freedom and adventure of the frontier. They built America.

12:02.000 --> 12:11.000
Pecos Bill, Part 1, Bill and the Coyotes.

12:11.000 --> 12:20.000
Pecos Bill was born in the east of the United States in the 1800s. He had a lot of brothers and sisters.

12:20.000 --> 12:24.000
Bill was the baby of the family.

12:24.000 --> 12:31.000
When Bill was about two years old, his mother and father decided to move to the west.

12:31.000 --> 12:37.000
They wanted to be pioneers. They liked the adventure of the frontier.

12:37.000 --> 12:43.000
One day they put all their possessions in a covered wagon and began their journey.

12:43.000 --> 12:49.000
The family crossed forests, mountains, rivers and plains.

12:49.000 --> 12:54.000
They saw many new things. They met friendly Indians.

12:54.000 --> 13:01.000
When they arrived in Texas, little Bill fell out of the covered wagon.

13:01.000 --> 13:08.000
His brothers and sisters didn't see him fall out. His parents didn't see him fall out.

13:08.000 --> 13:16.000
That evening, his parents looked for him. They looked everywhere, but they did not find little Bill.

13:16.000 --> 13:22.000
They were very sad, but they continued their journey.

13:22.000 --> 13:27.000
Little Bill was all alone in the plains of South Texas.

13:27.000 --> 13:36.000
He was an intelligent child. He looked around. He saw mountains, cacti and other small plants.

13:36.000 --> 13:45.000
It was very hot. Then he saw a cave. He went inside the cave and slept.

13:45.000 --> 13:49.000
He slept for a long time.

13:49.000 --> 13:57.000
In the cave there was a family of coyotes. There was a mother coyote and five small coyotes.

13:57.000 --> 14:02.000
The mother coyote liked little Bill. She decided to protect him.

14:02.000 --> 14:07.000
Bill liked his new mother and his new brothers and sisters.

14:07.000 --> 14:14.000
He played with the little coyotes. The coyote family was kind to him.

14:14.000 --> 14:23.000
He copied the coyotes and learned to run and eat. He learned to drink water from the river.

14:23.000 --> 14:27.000
At night, Bill howled at the moon with the coyotes.

14:27.000 --> 14:31.000
Bill learned to speak the language of the animals.

14:31.000 --> 14:38.000
Soon Bill forgot about his human family. He thought he was a coyote.

14:38.000 --> 14:43.000
Many years passed and Bill grew up.

14:43.000 --> 14:50.000
One day when he was about 20 years old, Bill was at the Pecos River with the other coyotes.

14:50.000 --> 14:53.000
He drank water with them.

14:53.000 --> 14:56.000
A cowboy saw him and asked,

14:56.000 --> 15:01.000
Why are you drinking water in that way? You aren't a coyote.

15:01.000 --> 15:04.000
Bill looked at the cowboy and said,

15:04.000 --> 15:07.000
Yes, I am.

15:07.000 --> 15:10.000
No, you're not a coyote.

15:10.000 --> 15:12.000
He said the cowboy.

15:12.000 --> 15:17.000
Of course I'm the coyote. This is my coyote family.

15:17.000 --> 15:18.000
Said Bill.

15:18.000 --> 15:20.000
Where's your tail?

15:20.000 --> 15:23.000
Ask the cowboy.

15:23.000 --> 15:28.000
Bill looked in the water of the Pecos River to see his reflection.

15:28.000 --> 15:35.000
He didn't see his tail. He looked and looked. He turned around and looked again.

15:35.000 --> 15:39.000
He was surprised. He didn't have a tail.

15:39.000 --> 15:43.000
You are right. I'm not a coyote.

15:43.000 --> 15:47.000
My name is Bill. I'm a human.

15:47.000 --> 15:49.000
This is a big surprise for me.

15:49.000 --> 15:57.000
He said the cowboy laughed and Bill laughed too.

15:57.000 --> 16:01.000
My name's Tall Tom and I'm a very tall cowboy.

16:01.000 --> 16:06.000
This is the Pecos River and I will call you Pecos Bill.

16:06.000 --> 16:10.000
Come with me, Pecos Bill. You can be a cowboy with me.

16:10.000 --> 16:13.000
We can work together at the Longhorn Ranch.

16:13.000 --> 16:17.000
Lots of cowboy asked Pecos Bill.

16:17.000 --> 16:21.000
A cowboy watches and guards the cattle and horses.

16:21.000 --> 16:24.000
He takes cattle from Texas to other places.

16:24.000 --> 16:28.000
People from the East by our cattle. They like good meat.

16:28.000 --> 16:33.000
A cowboy is a strong, courageous man.

16:33.000 --> 16:39.000
Pecos Bill wanted to be a cowboy. He said goodbye to the coyotes.

16:39.000 --> 16:43.000
He was sad to leave them. They were his friends.

16:43.000 --> 16:48.000
Then he said to Tall Tom, let's go to the ranch.

16:48.000 --> 16:52.000
The cowboy gave Pecos Bill some cowboy clothes.

16:52.000 --> 16:56.000
Pecos Bill looked at the clothes and laughed.

16:56.000 --> 16:59.000
Then he put them on.

16:59.000 --> 17:06.000
Tall Tom rode his horse. Pecos Bill walked near him because he didn't have a horse.

17:06.000 --> 17:15.000
It was a sunny day. The sky was blue and the sun was hot.

17:15.000 --> 17:18.000
Part Two

17:18.000 --> 17:21.000
King of the Cowboys

17:21.000 --> 17:26.000
Pecos Bill and Tall Tom traveled under the hot sun.

17:26.000 --> 17:32.000
It was a long journey. When they arrived at the mountains, it was evening.

17:32.000 --> 17:38.000
Pecos Bill said, I'm tired. Let's sit down and rest.

17:38.000 --> 17:44.000
That's a good idea, said Tall Tom. My horse is tired and thirsty.

17:44.000 --> 17:48.000
He gave his horse some water to drink.

17:48.000 --> 17:53.000
Pecos Bill and Tall Tom sat down under a big tree.

17:53.000 --> 17:58.000
There was a black bird in the tree. It sang a happy song.

17:58.000 --> 18:04.000
Pecos Bill knew the language of the animals, so he spoke to the black bird.

18:04.000 --> 18:13.000
They had a long conversation. Pecos Bill and Tall Tom ate some biscuits and drank some water.

18:13.000 --> 18:17.000
Pecos Bill gave the black bird some of his biscuit.

18:17.000 --> 18:20.000
Tall Tom sang a western song.

18:20.000 --> 18:29.000
But remember the Red River Valley and the one that has loved you so true.

18:29.000 --> 18:34.000
Pecos Bill liked it and asked, what's the name of the song?

18:34.000 --> 18:41.000
It's called Red River Valley. Many Cowboys in Texas sing it, said Tall Tom.

18:41.000 --> 18:46.000
Tall Tom made a fire and they talked about a cowboy's life.

18:46.000 --> 18:49.000
They looked at the stars in the night sky.

18:49.000 --> 18:56.000
Then they fell asleep. Early the next morning, they began their journey to the ranch.

18:56.000 --> 19:01.000
After two days, they finally arrived at the cattle ranch.

19:01.000 --> 19:05.000
The other cowboys were happy to meet Pecos Bill.

19:05.000 --> 19:08.000
Welcome to Long Horn Range.

19:08.000 --> 19:15.000
Said the cowboys, the ranch was very big. There were long horned cattle everywhere.

19:15.000 --> 19:19.000
They ate grass and drank water at the river.

19:19.000 --> 19:23.000
Pecos Bill saw the cowboys on their horses.

19:23.000 --> 19:27.000
Every cowboy had a long rope in his hands.

19:27.000 --> 19:33.000
I want to be a cowboy. Pecos Bill said to Tall Tom, what must I do?

19:33.000 --> 19:39.000
First, you must find a horse. Second, you must have a rope.

19:39.000 --> 19:43.000
Then we must take all the cattle to the Red River Valley.

19:43.000 --> 19:51.000
We must sell the cattle there. The Red River Valley is far away and it is a long, difficult journey.

19:51.000 --> 19:57.000
Pecos Bill looked around. He saw a black horse near a cactus.

19:57.000 --> 20:05.000
No one wanted to ride that horse. He went to the horse and talked to it in animal language.

20:05.000 --> 20:09.000
The horse didn't answer.

20:09.000 --> 20:14.000
Pecos Bill got on the horse. He tried to ride it.

20:14.000 --> 20:18.000
After a few moments, the black horse bucked him off.

20:18.000 --> 20:24.000
Pecos Bill tried again. The black horse bucked him off again.

20:24.000 --> 20:32.000
You're a bucking bronco. That's your new name, bucking bronco.

20:32.000 --> 20:35.000
Said Pecos Bill to the horse.

20:35.000 --> 20:43.000
Bucking bronco bucked Pecos Bill off for three days. He did not want a master.

20:43.000 --> 20:52.000
Pecos Bill was strong and determined. He wasn't afraid of bucking bronco. He wasn't afraid of anything.

20:52.000 --> 20:57.000
Bucking bronco was a beautiful horse, but he was very wild.

20:57.000 --> 21:02.000
On the fourth day, bucking bronco stopped bucking.

21:02.000 --> 21:09.000
He understood that Pecos Bill was a special cowboy. Pecos Bill was very strong.

21:09.000 --> 21:15.000
Bucking bronco knew that Pecos Bill was his new master.

21:15.000 --> 21:22.000
Pecos Bill and bucking bronco became good friends. Together they roped the cattle of Texas.

21:22.000 --> 21:27.000
Together they took cattle from Texas to other states.

21:27.000 --> 21:36.000
Pecos Bill became a famous cowboy. He was the best cowboy at the rodeos. Everyone knew him and liked him.

21:36.000 --> 21:40.000
He became the king of the cowboys of Texas.

21:40.000 --> 21:49.000
After a few years, Pecos Bill met a beautiful woman called Sue. She was very friendly.

21:49.000 --> 21:53.000
Her home was near the Rio Grande River.

21:53.000 --> 22:00.000
Pecos Bill loved her and she loved him. One sunny day in April, they got married.

22:00.000 --> 22:07.000
Everyone at the Longhorn Ranch celebrated the wedding. There was an exciting rodeo.

22:07.000 --> 22:12.000
There was music, dancing and a lot of good food.

22:12.000 --> 22:19.000
Supesam, the friendly cook, organized a pie-eating competition.

22:19.000 --> 22:25.000
Tall Tom's favorite food was apple pie. But he did not win the competition.

22:25.000 --> 22:36.000
His friend Big Bob won the pie-eating competition. Big Bob ate 88 apple pies.

22:36.000 --> 22:41.000
Pecos Bill and Sue were very happy at the Longhorn Ranch.

22:41.000 --> 22:48.000
Pecos Bill never forgot his friends the coyotes. And he never forgot the language of the animals.

22:48.000 --> 22:54.000
Life on a Ranch

22:54.000 --> 23:03.000
Cowboys usually lived and worked on a ranch. A ranch was a very big piece of land.

23:03.000 --> 23:12.000
There was usually only one owner of a ranch. There were cattle, sheep and horses on a ranch.

23:12.000 --> 23:16.000
Rodeos were a favorite pastime.

23:16.000 --> 23:21.000
When cowboys were at the ranch, they lived together in a bunk house.

23:21.000 --> 23:26.000
The owner of the ranch lived in another house.

23:26.000 --> 23:32.000
The cowboys ate together in a big room. Cowboys had big appetites.

23:32.000 --> 23:36.000
The cook was an important person.

23:36.000 --> 23:42.000
Cowboys often moved cattle to another place to sell them.

23:42.000 --> 23:49.000
Ten or twelve cowboys moved about 3,000 cattle. This was difficult work.

23:49.000 --> 23:57.000
They usually traveled for many weeks. They lived on the plains and in the mountains.

23:57.000 --> 24:04.000
They cooked their meals on an open fire. They slept under the stars.

24:04.000 --> 24:09.000
Sometimes it was very hot and other times it rained or snowed.

24:09.000 --> 24:15.000
Sometimes during the long journey, there were Indian attacks.

24:15.000 --> 24:19.000
When the cowboys sold the cattle, they were very happy.

24:19.000 --> 24:25.000
They stayed in a town for a few days. They bought new things.

24:25.000 --> 24:33.000
They went to the town Saloon. At the Saloon they played cards, drank whiskey and had a bath.

24:33.000 --> 24:41.000
Then they returned to their ranch. Today there are many cattle ranches in the United States.

24:41.000 --> 24:46.000
These ranches are in Texas and in the western states.

24:46.000 --> 24:55.000
Cowboys work on these ranches and they still ride horses.

24:55.000 --> 25:04.000
The Tale of Prayer Rabbit and the Tar Baby. Part 1. The Tar Baby.

25:04.000 --> 25:12.000
It was a hot day in August. Summer is a very hot season in the south of the United States.

25:12.000 --> 25:18.000
All the animals on the old plantation had a rest.

25:18.000 --> 25:28.000
Prayer Fox was outside his house. He sat under a magnolia tree and drank cold lemonade.

25:28.000 --> 25:34.000
He was very hot. He was also angry and nervous.

25:34.000 --> 25:38.000
Prayer Fox didn't like Prayer Rabbit.

25:38.000 --> 25:45.000
Before Prayer Rabbit came to the old plantation, Prayer Fox was a happy fox.

25:45.000 --> 25:51.000
The old plantation was a peaceful place. Prayer Rabbit tricked everyone.

25:51.000 --> 25:58.000
He tricked Prayer Bear, Prayer Turtle, Prayer Wolf and Prayer Fox.

25:58.000 --> 26:06.000
Prayer Rabbit was a very intelligent rabbit. He was young and dressed well.

26:06.000 --> 26:11.000
Prayer Fox was tired of Prayer Rabbit. He decided to trick him.

26:11.000 --> 26:19.000
He went to his garden and took a big bucket of tar. He put other oils in the bucket too.

26:19.000 --> 26:28.000
Then he mixed the tar for a long time. The tar had a terrible odor. It was very sticky.

26:28.000 --> 26:37.000
Prayer Fox went into his house. He went to the kitchen to look for an old straw hat, but he didn't find it.

26:37.000 --> 26:42.000
Then he went to the living room. He looked there too.

26:42.000 --> 26:51.000
Finally he went to the bedroom. In the bedroom he found an old straw hat, two buttons and a comb.

26:51.000 --> 26:58.000
He put them in a sack. Then he took the bucket of tar and walked to the road.

26:58.000 --> 27:04.000
He threw the tar near a log and made a big black tar baby.

27:04.000 --> 27:11.000
He put the old straw hat on the tar baby. He put on two buttons for the eyes.

27:11.000 --> 27:18.000
Then he put on the comb for the mouth. Prayer Fox looked at his work and was happy.

27:18.000 --> 27:24.000
The tar baby was ready. Prayer Fox hid behind a big tree.

27:24.000 --> 27:31.000
He waited for Prayer Rabbit to walk by. He waited and waited. It was very hot.

27:31.000 --> 27:39.000
After an hour, Prayer Rabbit walked down the road. He was very happy.

27:39.000 --> 27:43.000
He walked, jumped and sang a song.

27:43.000 --> 27:51.000
Prayer Fox watched him from behind the tree. Suddenly, Prayer Rabbit saw the tar baby.

27:51.000 --> 27:57.000
He stopped and looked at it. Prayer Rabbit was a friendly rabbit. He said,

27:57.000 --> 28:06.000
Good morning. It's a hot day today. The tar baby smiled but didn't answer.

28:06.000 --> 28:12.000
I am from the old plantation. Said Prayer Rabbit. Where are you from?

28:12.000 --> 28:20.000
The tar baby smiled but didn't answer. Prayer Fox watched everything from behind the tree.

28:20.000 --> 28:25.000
He wanted to laugh but he didn't. Prayer Rabbit tried again.

28:26.000 --> 28:33.000
Good morning. How are you? The tar baby smiled but didn't answer.

28:33.000 --> 28:39.000
What are you doing here? Where are you from? Prayer Rabbit asked again.

28:39.000 --> 28:48.000
The tar baby smiled but didn't answer. Prayer Rabbit was angry. His face and ears were red.

28:48.000 --> 28:55.000
Can you hear me? I said, Good morning. Why don't you answer me?

28:55.000 --> 29:01.000
He shouted. There was no answer. Prayer Rabbit was very angry.

29:01.000 --> 29:10.000
You are very unfriendly. I'm a friendly rabbit. I want to be your friend. Who are you?

29:10.000 --> 29:17.000
The tar baby didn't answer. Prayer Rabbit was furious. He hit the tar baby.

29:17.000 --> 29:21.000
His front paw was stuck in the tar baby's face.

29:21.000 --> 29:28.000
Prayer Fox was very happy. He laughed quietly. Let me go. Said Prayer Rabbit.

29:28.000 --> 29:34.000
The tar baby did not let go. Let me go. Said Prayer Rabbit again.

29:34.000 --> 29:41.000
Prayer Rabbit kicked the tar baby. Now his back paw was stuck in the tar baby's body.

29:41.000 --> 29:48.000
Please let me go. Shouted Prayer Rabbit. He kicked the tar baby again.

29:48.000 --> 29:54.000
Now his other back paw was stuck. Help! I can't move.

29:54.000 --> 30:00.000
Shouted. This is terrible. Poor Prayer Rabbit. He was covered with tar.

30:00.000 --> 30:06.000
His face and ears were black with tar. His paws were black with tar.

30:06.000 --> 30:09.000
He was a very unhappy rabbit.

30:12.000 --> 30:17.000
Exercise 6, page 67.

30:17.000 --> 30:24.000
Listen to the text and circle the words that are mentioned in each room.

30:24.000 --> 30:31.000
Let's look at Prayer Fox Manor. First let's go to the living room.

30:31.000 --> 30:37.000
In the living room there are books and there are two chairs.

30:37.000 --> 30:43.000
Now let's go to the kitchen. In the kitchen there's a table and a chair.

30:43.000 --> 30:49.000
There's a cup on the table. Now let's go to the bedroom.

30:49.000 --> 30:55.000
In the bedroom there's a bed, a clock and a jacket.

30:58.000 --> 31:04.000
Fox hunting. In Great Britain fox hunting is permitted.

31:04.000 --> 31:08.000
But many British people think it is cruel to hunt foxes.

31:08.000 --> 31:13.000
They want a law to stop fox hunting.

31:13.000 --> 31:20.000
In some states of the USA, fox hunting is still permitted.

31:20.000 --> 31:26.000
There are different types of foxes. The most popular is the red fox.

31:26.000 --> 31:29.000
It lives in Europe.

31:29.000 --> 31:35.000
The San Joaquin Kit Fox lives in the North American deserts.

31:35.000 --> 31:39.000
In the Arctic we find the white Arctic Fox.

31:39.000 --> 31:45.000
The Fennec Fox is very small and it has big ears.

31:45.000 --> 31:52.000
Today people want to help and protect animals, especially young animals.

31:53.000 --> 32:01.000
The WWF World Wildlife Fund defends animals all over the world.

32:04.000 --> 32:08.000
Part 2. The Briar Patch

32:08.000 --> 32:15.000
When Prayer Fox saw a prayer rabbit covered with tar, he laughed and laughed.

32:15.000 --> 32:19.000
He walked down the road and said,

32:19.000 --> 32:23.000
This is a good lesson for you prayer rabbit.

32:23.000 --> 32:27.000
You always tricked everyone on the old plantation.

32:27.000 --> 32:32.000
This time I tricked you. This is the end of prayer rabbit.

32:32.000 --> 32:38.000
Prayer Fox looked at prayer rabbit and laughed again.

32:38.000 --> 32:44.000
Prayer rabbit didn't say one word. He was frightened. He didn't move.

32:44.000 --> 32:47.000
Prayer Fox looked at his watch and said,

32:47.000 --> 32:52.000
It's dinner time and I'm very hungry.

32:52.000 --> 32:55.000
I want rabbit barbecue for dinner.

32:55.000 --> 33:02.000
Rabbit barbecue is delicious. I must find some wood to make a fire.

33:02.000 --> 33:05.000
Prayer Fox went to look for some wood.

33:05.000 --> 33:11.000
Prayer rabbit started to think. He was a very intelligent rabbit.

33:11.000 --> 33:16.000
His eyes moved from left to right. He looked everywhere.

33:16.000 --> 33:19.000
Then he saw a Briar Patch.

33:19.000 --> 33:26.000
The Briar Patch can take off the tar. But I can't move. I'm stuck.

33:26.000 --> 33:31.000
I must go to the Briar Patch. What can I do?

33:31.000 --> 33:33.000
Thought prayer rabbit.

33:33.000 --> 33:36.000
Prayer Fox returned and said,

33:36.000 --> 33:40.000
I didn't find any wood to make a fire.

33:40.000 --> 33:46.000
I can't have rabbit barbecue for dinner. But I can hang you.

33:46.000 --> 33:54.000
Oh, Prayer Fox. You can hang me. But please don't throw me in the Briar Patch.

33:54.000 --> 33:59.000
Said prayer rabbit. Prayer Fox looked for a rope.

33:59.000 --> 34:04.000
There's no rope. I can't hang you.

34:04.000 --> 34:08.000
How can I kill you? asked Prayer Fox.

34:08.000 --> 34:11.000
He thought for a moment and said,

34:11.000 --> 34:15.000
I can throw you in a river or a lake.

34:15.000 --> 34:19.000
Oh, Prayer Fox. Throw me in a river or a lake.

34:19.000 --> 34:25.000
But please don't throw me in the terrible Briar Patch. Please.

34:25.000 --> 34:29.000
Prayer Fox went to look for a river or a lake.

34:29.000 --> 34:33.000
He looked everywhere, but he didn't find a river or a lake.

34:33.000 --> 34:37.000
He was angry. He wanted to kill Prayer Rabbit.

34:37.000 --> 34:40.000
But how?

34:40.000 --> 34:47.000
Have you got a heart, Prayer Fox? Please don't throw me into the Briar Patch.

34:47.000 --> 34:51.000
Said prayer rabbit. Oh, please.

34:51.000 --> 34:54.000
Well. Said Prayer Fox smiling.

34:54.000 --> 34:58.000
You don't want to go into the Briar Patch.

34:58.000 --> 35:02.000
That's exactly where I will throw you.

35:02.000 --> 35:05.000
Into the Briar Patch.

35:05.000 --> 35:09.000
Prayer Fox threw Prayer Rabbit into the Briar Patch.

35:09.000 --> 35:12.000
This was exactly what Prayer Rabbit wanted.

35:12.000 --> 35:17.000
The tar baby stuck to the Briar Patch and Prayer Rabbit was free.

35:17.000 --> 35:22.000
When Prayer Fox saw the tar baby in the Briar Patch, he asked.

35:22.000 --> 35:27.000
What's happening? Where is that cunning rabbit?

35:27.000 --> 35:31.000
Why is the tar baby here?

35:31.000 --> 35:35.000
Prayer Rabbit ran up the road and then stopped.

35:35.000 --> 35:38.000
He looked at Prayer Fox and said,

35:38.000 --> 35:46.000
You didn't listen to me. I said, please don't throw me into the Briar Patch.

35:46.000 --> 35:49.000
Next time you'll listen to me.

35:49.000 --> 35:53.000
Prayer Rabbit laughed and ran home to have a bath.

35:53.000 --> 35:59.000
You horrible cunning rabbit. You tricked me again.

35:59.000 --> 36:03.000
Said Prayer Fox, he was purple with anger.

36:03.000 --> 36:07.000
He looked at the Briar Patch and he looked at the tar baby.

36:07.000 --> 36:12.000
Then he walked home slowly. He was very sad and angry.

36:12.000 --> 36:18.000
Prayer Rabbit tricked him again. Why was Prayer Rabbit so intelligent?

36:18.000 --> 36:24.000
When Prayer Fox went into his garden, he sat down under the magnolia tree.

36:24.000 --> 36:28.000
He was tired. He looked at the evening sky.

36:28.000 --> 36:33.000
The stars and the moon and fell asleep.

36:35.000 --> 36:40.000
Prayer Tales and the South

36:40.000 --> 36:44.000
Welcome to the South and welcome to the old plantation.

36:44.000 --> 36:49.000
The people of the South are famous for their hospitality.

36:49.000 --> 36:56.000
Prayer Tales were told about 200 years ago on the plantations of the South.

36:56.000 --> 37:02.000
The children of the plantations listened to these tales about funny animal characters.

37:02.000 --> 37:06.000
Everyone loved Prayer Tales.

37:06.000 --> 37:13.000
In 1880, the American writer Joel Chandler Harris published these tales.

37:13.000 --> 37:20.000
His book was called Uncle Remus, His Songs and Sayings.

37:20.000 --> 37:24.000
Harris created a character named Uncle Remus.

37:24.000 --> 37:29.000
Uncle Remus told the tales and everyone liked him.

37:29.000 --> 37:35.000
There is also a film about Uncle Remus and his tales.

37:35.000 --> 37:42.000
In the 1700s and 1800s, there were many plantations in the South.

37:42.000 --> 37:50.000
Tobacco, cotton and sugar cane were the most important products of the plantations.

37:51.000 --> 37:56.000
Every plantation had a big, beautiful house and garden.

37:56.000 --> 37:59.000
The owners of the plantation lived there.

37:59.000 --> 38:06.000
Today, in the South of the United States, you can visit old plantation houses.

38:20.000 --> 38:26.000
Thanks for watching!

